@PaulProtagonist This is one of the world record holders, she's a cis woman and she's 6'4". Don't you think it's unfair that she gets to swim when the average for female swimmers is 5'9"? https://t.co/ruevSH6oYg

@PaulProtagonist Okay? But she's on testosterone blockers and she's on estrogen. She's breaking world records because she's a great swimmer, if she was a cis woman we would just say she's great in what she does.

Also yes trans women without blockers MAY be able to build muscle quicker, you have just made the assumption that men, in professional sports are stronger' when that isn't true. It's sexist to assume that cis women couldn't beat a trans woman because of a bit if extra muscle.

The same way that a 6ft swimmer has an advantage on a 5'8 swimmer because their wingspan is longer but that a 5'8 swimmer maybe lighter and so slightly faster. This is not a debate for sports people. It is not a debate for non-specialist doctors. It is not a debate.

But trans people may or may not have medically transitioned, they maybe somewhere in the middle of medical transition, they may be taller or shorter,heavier or lighter etc. Trans people aren't just one thing, we are also intricate people.

People like @MichaelPhelps weighing in on the 'trans sports debate' is a problem because they don't look into the intricacies of being trans. To them a trans woman is a man with testosterone in their body, wearing a bathing suit. They have no research to back up their ideas.
And futhermore doesn't even make sense because people who complain about trans men in women's sports are saying exactly what we are. Trans men should play in men's sports.

Trans men are never brought into the debate until they're playing in a women's sport. The argument is, trans men will be biologically stronger (same stupid idea as before). This doesn't take into account if they are on testosterone hormone therapy or not.
Trans women are AMAB which in general makes them taller on average and therefore heavier, in a sport like swimming that can actually disadvantage you against cis women.

However, many trans women are on hormone blockers which stops testosterone being produced in the body and are on estrogen hormones meaning that their ability to build muscle and to retain muscle will be the same as a cis woman.

This debate is only ever raised when trans women is play in women's sports. Not when trans men play in men's sports. Why? SEXISM. YES people with testosterone in their bodies will naturally be able to build muscle faster hence the incorrect idea 'Men are stronger'

I will keep you updated if anybody else has anymore  weird dreams or sees this man in their dreams or whatever but it just freaked me out a bit.

I can't even explain to you how strange he is, like theatre people can be very pretentious and kinda weird anyway but this is another level. It's like he doesn't really know how to act like a human. I thought It was fucking funny but I genuinely am a bit like WTF.

So I started talking to my group about the guy that a lot of people have seen in their dream and they knew what I was on about and whilst we were working I looked up and realised something. Our speaker looks like this guy!

He was also really weird about us talking about the nightmares we have had like he was happy to hear about them and like they were like really interesting to him. Then he made us create them as art but some of the stuff we talked about was terrifying for others.

So me and a friend thought this was weird and wrote it all down to write a script about our speaker being an alien or whatever who is just using these sessions to learn about dreams and how they work.

Like about dreams. So we start talking about nightmares and sleep paralysis and he says he's never heard of a falling dream or sleep paralysis or like basically any of the stuff we talked about like this man has never once had a dream.

So skip foward to today and we have him again and he has shaved his beard off and I was making jokes about how baby faced he looks. So we do the warm up etc and then he sits us down and says that our project is gonna be about dreams and he wants us to tel  us what we know.
So we has him the next day and he was kinda strange but not any more abnormal than most drama people. We were focusing on movement so forgot about all the dream BS right?
Like really horrible stuff right? Most people had a really bad experiences in this theatre session with this outside speaker and left feeling like shit, having bad dreams, etc.

So I ask what I missed in the session and a few people said that they started a new module and that we had a new outside speaker to teach this module. So this guy did a session about dreaming with them and some of them had some horrible things happen.

So I remember that being a thing and I never saw this man in my dreams so I was like okay whatever, it's just psychology right? So last week I missed a university session (I study theatre) because I had a hospital appointment.
